Rating: 4
I've been making these cookies since 2000 when they first showed up on Epicurious. I can't recommend this recipe enough - I made them again yesterday and was curious to see the latest comments on the recipe. It's probably too late, but a poster in 3/08 mentioned her melted chocolate chips didn't melt - that it just turned into a paste. It sounds like your chocolate seized - either it was over-heated or you may have gotten some water in there. The chocolate should be thoroughly melted and velvety - like a fondue. You can avoid seizing by definitely using the double boiler as the recipe says. If you don't have a double-boiler, just put a metal bowl over a pan of simmering water. Important: do not let the bowl touch the simmering water! You want steam, not contact with the heat. Melt slowly and evenly and stir a lot - don't rush the process. I hope this helps you and any other bakers that encounter this problem - please try the cookies again, you won't be disappointed! I use Ghirardelli bittersweet chocolate bars and Skor toffee bars. As some other reviewers said, I chop the Skor bars very coarsely so there are nice big chunks of toffee. I also would not leave out the toasted walnuts - they give the cookies great complexity in flavor and texture. To me, the cookies are better when thoroughly cooled. I use parchment paper every time - I would not mess with waxed paper. Good luck and enjoy!

