Rating: 4
Definitely worth making. I went with 3/4 C flour (the thinness of the unchilled dough scared me), double the salt, and coarsely broken Heath bars. Maybe I didn't need to worry about the thinness - by the time it was chilled in the frig, I just about bent a spoon trying to get the dough out of the bowl and onto the pans. The cookies both tasted great and kept a good shape. (I kept the dough in the refrigerator till I dropped them on each cookie sheet.) And because they're so rich, you need not make them so large. With the first batch I made large ones as the recipe said - and they are impressive - although the bigger they were, the flatter they looked. After that I went smaller, which I prefer. I cooled the cookies completely on the parchment paper (I just slid each batch off the hot cookie sheet onto my granite counter), then moved them off the paper when cooled. At the office 5 women tasted them and the cookies got 2 wows, one amazing, and one lady said she had to sit down to enjoy it.

Rating: 4
Also, I made regular sized cookies and it made over 60! And, as mentioned below, the dough does work better chilled.

