Rating: 4
I have been making these cookies for years and they are my husband's favorite. A tip for those of you having trouble making the toffee bars into chunks: use a hammer to break the chocolate bars into chunks while they are still in their wrappers. This method is quick and it will give you nice big chunks (don't over beat them!) and keeping them in the wrapper will prevent your kitchen from becoming a total mess.

Rating: 4
Always a hit in my house! We like to make them a little smaller so we don't feel guilty eating them 2 at a time.

Rating: 4
This recipe won me my office's annual cookie competition! For smaller cookies, I used a #40 cookie scoop and cooked them for 9-10 minutes. I cut Heath Bites into quarters, and used 2 (so 1/2 a Bite) per small cookie. For the regular (1/4 cup) size cookies, I found that cutting the Bites into halves and using 4 (so 2 Bites total) per cookie worked well. Definitely give the large cookies a second chill after portioning them (around 20 minutes, like others have suggested). The smaller cookies get dry if you put them back in the fridge for a second chill before baking, so just bake after portioning. For the first chill, just after making the batter, I like to let it refrigerate overnight.

Rating: 4
I followed the suggestions of previous reviewers and substituted almonds and Heath Bar Bites. As I was mixing the batter I realized I was out of vanilla extract so I substituted almond extract. (A little too almond-y; next time I'll do half and half). I beat the eggs and sugar for 5 minutes on high and waited until chocolate was almost fully cool. The dough was VERY thick (but sticky). After refrigerating ~ 1 hour, I dropped by tablespoon and ended up with ~6 dozen 1-1/2 inch cookies. I baked for only 11 minutes. The results were very light (almost like a macaroon) but rich and chocolately. YUM!! This recipe is definitely a keeper.

Rating: 4
I have made these cookies several times over the past three yeasrs. EVERYONE loves them and requests them. As I've gotten older, I've gotten bored with the standard chocolate chip or sugar cookies. These are a nice addition to any baker's recipe box. A few tips - I use the mini size Heath bars that come in bags. I do not crush into teeny tiny pieces. Instead, I pound them into small chunks. Do not use the bits. These cookies will not turn out as good. I found that Skor bars didn't work as well either. Do NOT use chocolate chips. For the most part, the chocolate in chocolate chips is not high quality. Instead high quality baking bars. Much easier to measure than chips as well. Refrigerate the dough suffiently. Depending on where you live, 40 minutes may not be enough. Make sure the dough is sturdy when you remove from the fridge. I have never had runny cookies. Watch these cookies CAREFULLY. They burn easily, especially with the toffee and nuts. I made the mistake of walking away once to return to gross throwaways. Use silpats if you can. Personally, I suggest making the cookies smaller than what's recommended in the recipe. They are very rich, and the big cookie almost detracts from the overall flavor and look of the cookie. I've made these dozens of times, and haven't had any of the problems people have mentioned. These would be great for a holiday cookie exchange or bake sale, although I can never make them last more than a few days in my house.

