Rating: 3
Very intense cookies. I used Bakers chocolate, 3/4 semisweet and 1/4 unsweetened, and Trader Joe's toffee chopped in large chunks. They fell somewhere in between the reviews, not large and cakey, but not flat either. However, I used the baking soda test that another reviewer suggested (afterward, before baking some other cookies), and mine appeared not to be very active. What I did have happen to these cookies was that they slumped and melted randomly depending on where the toffee bits were. For this reason I might suggest using smaller toffee bits, but then you lose the effect of the big chunks. Tradeoff. I also was able to improve the problem by by flattening the cookies into circles before baking. The toffee bits still melted, but they cookies turned out much more evenly shaped and baked. I baked the cookies right on a metal sheet rubbed with vegetable oil, and I found that if I loosened them right after I took them out of the oven, they wouldn't stick, and I could also sort of push the spilled melted toffee back toward the cookie. I experimented, and discovered I liked the 1/4 cup size best cooked for only 12 minutes, but since they're so rich I preferred 1/8 cup sized cookies, baked for 10 minutes. Don't let them cook until they *look* done. They *will* burn on the bottom, and you won't know it until later. Also, I served these a few minutes out of the oven with a scoop of french vanilla ice cream and homemade caramel sauce. Yummy. I even got a "to die for" out of my mom, who usually avoids sweets. My dad liked the dough unbaked. With the high chocolate content, it's just like fudge (but with raw eggs, so of course I can't recommend it).

