Rating: 4
I've made this recipe a couple dozen times and rate it as the best cookie recipe I have. They are great hot, are even better the 2nd day and can keep for several days, which makes them great for a make ahead dessert or for mailing. They have an addictive rich chocolate taste and a great chewy texture. The following tips may help if you tried them and they didn't turn out. Take heart, my first attempt was an unqualified mess. First, some chocolate chips melt completely (become liquid) with butter and some end up more like playdoh. Either will work for the recipe. However, if the chocolate melts completely then you will need to refrigerate the dough for several hours. Otherwise the cookies spread like pancakes. In general, I've found that thoroughly refrigerating the dough (at least 2 hours) brings about better results. I've used chopped toffee and toffee bits and, frankly, they both work. The chopped toffee makes a first class cookie but in a pinch (or if you're short on time) the bits will work too. Wax paper is a bad, bad idea. I've never had a good turn out with these cookies and wax paper. Parchment is terrific. However, if parchment isn't a part of your kitchen, you can simply grease the pan between batches and remove the cookies within a minute or two of taking them from the oven (otherwise they will stick and break apart). You do have to keep greasing the pan though or the cookies will be difficult to remove. My last tip is that I highly recommend using unsalted butter (as indicated in the recipe). Otherwise the cookies will cross the line to being too salty to taste good. I hope these suggestions help. These cookies are really too good to miss!!

