Rating: 4
These really are the best they rival any cookies selling in posh NYC bake shops. Here are some additional tips that I found: do a combination of bittersweet and semi-sweet chocolate, use toasted pecans instead of walnuts, press the cookie batter down before baking and again when they come out of the oven and do not be afraid to make smaller cookies so that there are more to savor. These are THE BEST !!!!

Rating: 3
These cookies came out picture perfect. I didnt use any waxed paper just a good old nonstick cookie sheet. I omitted the walnuts and added pecans instead. These are the chewiest richest chocolate cookies I have ever had and are stupendous with a glass of milk. I will definitly make them again!

Rating: 4
WOW WOW WOW!! These cookies are far and away the best chocolate cookies I have ever tasted. I know that sounds melodramatic, but it's true...they are absolutely delicious. An added bonus is how beautiful they turned out. I think they'd be great as a gift for someone, nicely wrapped in a pastry box. The recipe isn't hard, but I didn't think it was "easy" as some have mentioned, simply because I thought it took a bit of time to make. But that's probably because I don't have a big enough oven to make a big batch at a time. These cookies are divine,thank you, Bon Apetit!!

Rating: 4
Incredible! Everyone wants this recipe. Easy and fun. Will definitely make again.

Rating: 4
These cookies are awesome.I made them the very day my issue arrived, because the photo on the cover commanded me to. I omitted the walnuts. They were very easy to make and cam our beautifully. My husband and I each ate a warm one, and we were groaning at how good they were. I was surprised to find that the toffee had completely melted. Then I had a room-temp one the next day with a cup of coffee and it was even better! And I found that when they cool, the toffee rehardens, but not in clumps. So they are crisp and gooey at the same time. If you like rich, chocolatey cookies, these are the cookies for you.

